The Honours Bachelor of Commerce (Digital Marketing) program at George Brown College lasts for four years and includes capstone courses, a work placement semester, and opportunities to network with industry practitioners through guest lectures, business and marketing networking events, competitions, and on-campus clubs. Students will complete a co-op paid work term and have access to membership in the Canadian Marketing Association (CMA) and Interactive Advertising Bureau (IAB), which includes benefits such as live and online events, professional development opportunities, networking with thousands of marketers, digital marketing research, and globally standardized courses and certification. Graduates will be prepared for careers in digital marketing roles in various industries and organizations, emphasizing ethical and accountable work practices and entrepreneurial and business acumen.

The Honours Bachelor of Commerce (Digital Marketing) program offered by the college requires students to complete 40 courses in total, including one integrated work experience term. Students need to finish 34 mandatory courses and six liberal arts courses of their choice. The first semester includes courses like Canadian Business Fundamentals, Financial Mathematics, Microeconomics, Applied Business Communication, and Business Management Information Systems. The second semester consists of Marketing Management, Introduction to Financial Accounting, Macroeconomics, Organizational Behaviour, Critical Thinking and Problem Solving, Marketing Strategy, Managerial Accounting I, Canadian Business Law, and Statistical Methods. Students with a GPA of 3.0 or higher from an Ontario College Diploma in Business-Marketing may be awarded advanced standing into year three of the program. Graduates can pursue further study options in master's level courses at various post-secondary institutions across Canada.

5. Analyze qualitative and quantitative data to solve marketing and organization problems.
6. Design marketing strategy to meet business and organization needs.
7. Create marketing communication plans and tactics using digital marketing concepts, models, frameworks and tools.
8. Evaluate and use digital media channels and platforms to deliver marketing communication.

  - Recommended courses include basic computer software applications and Mathematics of Data Management (MDM4U).
  - Mature student status (19 years of age or older and no OSSD).
